Naturally, or in reference to Nature, according to Aristotle's way of thinking, the universal is prior to the individual, the cause to the effect, the general law to the particular fact. By or in reference to us, on the other hand, the individual is better known than the universal, the effect than the cause, the particular fact than the general law. Nature indeed may be regarded as ever striving to reproduce the type in the individuai‚ to represent the general law in its special manifestations, to carry out the cause into its effects. And so, bya figure of speech, it may he said to have a better or prior knowledge of that which, in our case, comes last, und as the result oia variety of mental operations.
